%[text] # A09: PFAS and Environmental Chemical Screening
%[text] When unknown chemicals turn up in groundwater near manufacturing facilities, we automatically determine which are PFAS (Per- and Polyfluoroalkyl Substances) -- the so-called "forever chemicals."
%[text] PFAS are a group of over 9,000 synthetic chemicals used in non-stick coatings and firefighting foams since the 1940s.
%[text] The bond dissociation energy of the C-F bond (carbon-fluorine bond) is approximately 544 kJ/mol, making it highly resistant to biological and environmental degradation.
%[text] By combining SMARTS patterns (a query language for searching molecular structures) with physicochemical scoring, you can automatically narrow down many candidates and prioritize them according to environmental risk.
%[text] In this tutorial, we work through PFAS screening, persistence scoring, weight optimization, and Tanimoto similarity analysis in four stages -- taking the perspective of an environmental toxicologist at a water quality management agency.
%[text] ### Learning Objectives
%[text] - Understand the structural definition of PFAS (OECD 2021 criteria)
%[text] - Apply multi-pattern SMARTS screening with `emk.mol.hasSubstruct()`
%[text] - Develop the concept of quantifying expert knowledge as a numerical concern score
%[text] - Understand the flow of constrained weight optimization problems using fmincon
%[text] - Interpret structural clusters with a Tanimoto similarity heatmap \
%[text] ### Workflow (4 Stages)
%[text] 1. **PFAS Flagging** -- Detect perfluoroalkyl chains, CF3 terminals, and sulfonyl head groups with SMARTS
%[text] 2. **Persistence Scoring** -- Estimate environmental persistence with three proxies: LogP, number of fluorines, and TPSA
%[text] 3. **Multi-Criteria Prioritization** -- Use fmincon to find optimal weights for the reference rubric
%[text] 4. **Report** -- Create a ranked concern table, scatter plots, and Tanimoto similarity heatmap \
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of A07 (Scaffold Analysis) -- Understanding of SMARTS and substructure concepts
%[text] - Optimization Toolbox (fmincon) -- Required for Section 4 (automatic fallback to equal weights if unavailable)
%[text] - Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox -- Required for Section 5 (`clusterdata`, `linkage`, `dendrogram`)
%[text] - Both toolboxes are included in MATLAB Online Basic (free tier) \
%[text] ### Data: 
%[text] - All molecules are defined inline (SMILES literals), no external files needed (US EPA CompTox + OECD 2021 criteria). \
%[text] Estimated time required: 35-50 minutes | Execution method: Run each section one by one with Ctrl+Enter
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup

% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:941ab330]

%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process before main execution.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;

%[text] Check available toolboxes.
hasOptTbx   = license("test", "optimization_toolbox");
hasStatsTbx = license("test", "statistics_toolbox");

if hasOptTbx %[output:group:368aeeec]
    logInfo("A09: Optimization Toolbox detected -- weight optimization enabled."); %[output:2d94b415]
else
    logWarn("A09: Optimization Toolbox not detected.");
    logWarn("     Section 4 will use equal weight fallback.");
end %[output:group:368aeeec]

if hasStatsTbx %[output:group:568707ad]
    logInfo("A09: Statistics and ML Toolbox detected -- hierarchical clustering enabled."); %[output:60b414cb]
else
    logWarn("A09: Statistics and ML Toolbox not detected.");
    logWarn("     Clustering in Section 5 will be skipped.");
end %[output:group:568707ad]

logSection("A09", "Section 0: Setup", "Analytics L3"); %[output:14d5981a]
logInfo("A09: Setup complete."); %[output:65593e0d]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Definition of Test Chemical Inventory
%[text] We begin by defining an inventory of 20 chemicals -- a realistic environmental screening set spanning 4 PFAS subclasses and non-PFAS controls.
%[text] ### Concept: What is PFAS?
%[text] According to the OECD (2021) definition, PFAS are "substances that contain at least one perfluorinated methyl (-CF3) or methylene (-CF2-) carbon atom."
%[text] However, substances where all C-F bonds are directly attached to heteroatoms (non-carbon atoms) (e.g., -CF2Cl, SF6) are excluded.
%[text] The four main structural classes of PFAS are:
%[text] **(1) Perfluoroalkyl Carboxylic Acids (PFCAs)**
%[text] The general formula is F-(CF2)n-COOH, with a fully fluorinated carbon chain and a terminal carboxylic acid (-COOH).
%[text] Examples: PFOA (n=7), PFBA (n=3), PFHxA (n=5).
%[text] SMARTS flag: Repeated perfluoroalkyl chain `[C](F)(F)(F)` or `[CF2]`.
%[text] **(2) Perfluoroalkyl Sulfonic Acids (PFSAs)**
%[text] The general formula is F-(CF2)n-SO3H, with a terminal sulfonic acid (-SO3H) on the fluorinated chain.
%[text] Examples: PFOS (n=8), PFBS (n=4), PFHxS (n=6).
%[text] SMARTS flag: Combined with perfluoroalkyl chain `-S(=O)(=O)O`.
%[text] **(3) Fluorotelomer Substances (FTS / FTOH)**
%[text] Structure is F-(CF2)n-CH2CH2-, a polyfluoroalkyl precursor with a hydrocarbon (C-H bond) at the end of the fluorinated chain.
%[text] These are precursor chemicals that degrade into PFCA in the environment, using fluorotelomer alcohol (FTOH) with a head group of -OH in this set, unified under the class label "FTS".
%[text] SMARTS flag: `-CF2-CH2-` junction.
%[text] **(4) Non-PFAS Fluorinated Compounds (NonPFAS)**
%[text] Includes drugs (Fluoxetine, Ciprofloxacin) and pesticides (Flurbiprofen), which have isolated C-F bonds but no perfluoroalkyl chains.
%[text] SMARTS flag: Classified as non-PFAS due to failing the perfluoroalkyl chain test.
%[text] The 20 test set covers all 4 classes and includes controls from the US EPA CompTox PFAS Universe list.
%[text] Each entry is in the format `{Display Name, SMILES, True Class Label}`, with class labels being either "PFCA", "PFSA", "FTS", or "NonPFAS".
logSection("A09", "Section 1: Definition of Test Chemical Inventory", "Analytics L3"); %[output:0b53c996]
CHEMICALS = { ...
    % --- PFCAs (Perfluoroalkyl Carboxylic Acids) ---
    "PFBA",    "OC(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F",                           "PFCA";    ...  % C4 PFCA: COOH-CF2-CF2-CF3 (4 carbons, fully fluorinated)
    "PFHxA",   "OC(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F",           "PFCA";    ...  % C6 PFCA
    "PFOA",    "OC(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F", "PFCA"; ...  % C8 PFCA (OECD Annex B substance)
    "PFNA",    "OC(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F","PFCA"; ... % C9 PFCA
    "PFDA",    "OC(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F","PFCA"; ... % C10 PFCA
    % --- PFSAs (Perfluoroalkyl Sulfonic Acids) ---
    "PFBS",    "OS(=O)(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F",               "PFSA";    ...  % C4 PFSA: SO3H-CF2-CF2-CF2-CF3 (4 carbons, fully fluorinated)
    "PFHxS",   "OS(=O)(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F","PFSA";    ...  % C6 PFSA
    "PFOS",    "OS(=O)(=O)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F","PFSA"; ... % C8 PFSA (Stockholm Convention Annex B)
    % --- Fluorotelomers and Polyfluoroalkyl Precursors ---
    "6:2FTS",  "OCCC(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F",       "FTS";     ...  % 6:2 Fluorotelomer Sulfonate
    "8:2FTS",  "OCCC(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F","FTS"; ... % 8:2 Fluorotelomer
    "4:2FTS",  "OCCC(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)C(F)(F)F",                     "FTS";     ...  % 4:2 Fluorotelomer
    % --- Non-PFAS Fluorinated Pharmaceuticals and Pesticides (Controls) ---
    "Fluoxetine", "CNCCC(c1ccccc1)Oc1ccc(cc1)C(F)(F)F",                 "NonPFAS"; ...  % Antidepressant (1 trifluoromethyl)
    "Ciprofloxacin","OC(=O)c1cn(C2CCNCC2)c2cc(F)c(nc12)N1CCCC1",        "NonPFAS"; ...  % Antibiotic (1 C-F)
    "Flurbiprofen","OC(=O)C(C)c1ccc(cc1)-c1cccc(F)c1",                  "NonPFAS"; ...  % NSAID (1 C-F)
    "Diflunisal","OC(=O)c1ccc(cc1O)-c1ccc(F)cc1F",                      "NonPFAS"; ...  % NSAID (2 isolated C-F)
    "Trifluridine","OC1C(CO)OC(n2cc(c(=O)[nH]2)C(F)(F)F)C1F",           "NonPFAS"; ...  % Antiviral (mixed halogenation)
    "Halothane","FC(F)(F)C(Cl)Br",                                       "NonPFAS"; ...  % Anesthetic (3F but on 1C, no chain)
    "Sevoflurane","FC(F)(F)C(F)OCC(F)(F)F",                              "NonPFAS"; ...  % Volatile anesthetic
    "Flecainide","OCC(NC(=O)c1cc(OCC(F)(F)F)c(cc1OCC(F)(F)F)OCC(F)(F)F)CC", "NonPFAS"; ... % Antiarrhythmic (OCH2CF3 group)
    "Ethanol",  "CCO",                                                   "NonPFAS"; ...  % Negative control (no F)
};

nChem   = size(CHEMICALS, 1);
names   = string(CHEMICALS(:,1));
smiles  = string(CHEMICALS(:,2));
trueCls = string(CHEMICALS(:,3));

logInfo("Inventory: %d chemicals (PFCA %d, PFSA %d, FTS %d, NonPFAS %d)", ... %[output:group:3d31f5ef] %[output:6e6c13ba]
    nChem, sum(trueCls=="PFCA"), sum(trueCls=="PFSA"), ... %[output:6e6c13ba]
    sum(trueCls=="FTS"),  sum(trueCls=="NonPFAS")); %[output:group:3d31f5ef] %[output:6e6c13ba]

%[text] Parse each SMILES with RDKit (convert to molecular objects).
mols  = cell(1, nChem);
valid = false(1, nChem);
for k = 1:nChem
    try
        mols{k} = emk.mol.fromSmiles(smiles(k));
        valid(k) = true;
    catch ME
        logWarn("Cannot parse %s: %s", names(k), ME.message);
    end
end
logInfo("Parsed %d / %d molecules.", sum(valid), nChem); %[output:6716fdb5]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: SMARTS-based PFAS Flagging
%[text] With the inventory defined, we now automatically flag each molecule as PFAS or non-PFAS using SMARTS patterns.
%[text] ### Concept: SMARTS Patterns for PFAS Detection
%[text] SMARTS (SMiles ARbitrary Target Specification) is a language for encoding structural queries with constraints on atoms and bonds.
%[text] Unlike SMILES, which describes a specific molecule, SMARTS is used to describe "structural motifs common to many molecules."
%[text] The key SMARTS atomic symbols used here are:
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Symbol | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | `[#6]` | Any carbon atom (atomic number 6) |
%[text] | `[F]` | Fluorine atom |
%[text] | `[#16]` | Any sulfur atom (atomic number 16) |
%[text] | `[!F]` | Any atom that is not fluorine |
%[text] | `[\\$(...)]` | Recursive SMARTS (nested subquery) |
%[text:table]
%[text] To cover the OECD PFAS structural definition, we combine three complementary patterns.
%[text] **(A) Perfluoroalkyl Chain**: `[#6](F)(F)-[#6](F)(F)`
%[text] Matches when a carbon bonded to exactly two Fs is bonded to an adjacent carbon of the same structure.
%[text] This is the -CF2-CF2- signature of a fully fluorinated carbon chain, requiring at least two consecutive CF2 units.
%[text] **(B) Trifluoromethyl Terminal**: `[#6](F)(F)F`
%[text] Matches the -CF3 at the end of a perfluoroalkyl chain.
%[text] Also matches isolated CF3 groups (control compounds), so (B) alone is too broad for PFAS identification.
%[text] Reliable PFAS flagging requires combination with (A).
%[text] **(C) Sulfonyl Head Group**: `[#16](=O)(=O)`
%[text] Matches the -S(=O)(=O)- core (sulfonic acid/sulfonamide skeleton). Combined with (A), it identifies PFSA.
%[text] The flagging logic combines these patterns as follows:
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Variable | Condition | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | `hasChain` | Matches pattern (A) | Presence of a fully perfluoroalkyl chain |
%[text] | `hasCF3` | Matches pattern (B) | Presence of CF3 group (may be isolated) |
%[text] | `hasSulfonyl` | Matches pattern (C) | Presence of sulfonic acid/sulfonamide head group |
%[text] | `isPFAS` | `hasChain == true` | PFAS if perfluoroalkyl chain is present |
%[text:table]
%[text] Compounds identified as PFAS are further subclassified into PFSA / FTS / PFCA based on the presence of `hasSulfonyl`.
%[text] Note that this rule-based classifier is for illustrative purposes and not regulatory grade.
%[text] Actual PFAS screening workflows (e.g., EPA DSSTox) use large SMARTS libraries with hundreds of patterns.
logSection("A09", "Section 2: SMARTS-based PFAS Flagging", "Analytics L3"); %[output:508a0461]
SMARTS_PFCHAIN  = "[#6](F)(F)-[#6](F)(F)";    % CF2-CF2 backbone
SMARTS_CF3      = "[#6](F)(F)F";              % -CF3 terminal
SMARTS_SULFONYL = "[#16](=O)(=O)";            % -SO2- head group
SMARTS_POLYFLUORO = "[#6](F)(F)[#6H2]";          % CF2 directly bonded to CH2 (FTS junction only)

validMols = mols(valid);
validNames = names(valid);
validSmiles = smiles(valid);
validCls = trueCls(valid);
nValid = sum(valid);

%[text] Apply each SMARTS pattern to all valid molecules to obtain flags.
hasChain    = emk.mol.hasSubstruct(validMols, SMARTS_PFCHAIN);
hasCF3      = emk.mol.hasSubstruct(validMols, SMARTS_CF3);
hasSulfonyl = emk.mol.hasSubstruct(validMols, SMARTS_SULFONYL);
hasPolyFluoro = emk.mol.hasSubstruct(validMols, SMARTS_POLYFLUORO);

%[text] Molecules with a perfluoroalkyl chain (hasChain) are identified as PFAS.
%[text] `hasCF3 & hasChain` is effectively equivalent to `isPFAS = hasChain` since it is a subset of `hasChain` (redundant terms are retained for clarity).
isPFAS = hasChain | (hasCF3 & hasChain);

%[text] Classify PFAS hits into subclasses based on the presence of hasSulfonyl and FTS patterns.
classGuess = repmat("NonPFAS", nValid, 1);
for k = 1:nValid
    if isPFAS(k)
        if hasSulfonyl(k)
            classGuess(k) = "PFSA";
        elseif hasPolyFluoro(k) && ~hasSulfonyl(k)
            classGuess(k) = "FTS";
        else
            classGuess(k) = "PFCA";
        end
    end
end

%[text] Compare with true labels to check the number of correctly classified cases.
nPFAS_hit = sum(isPFAS);
nPFAS_true = sum(validCls ~= "NonPFAS");
correct = sum(classGuess == validCls);

logInfo("PFAS Flagging Results:"); %[output:071fa050]
logInfo("  True PFAS: %d    Detected PFAS: %d    Correct Classification: %d / %d", ... %[output:group:6e3b6aad] %[output:089887d5]
    nPFAS_true, nPFAS_hit, correct, nValid); %[output:group:6e3b6aad] %[output:089887d5]

%[text] Display the results in a table. TrueClass=correct label, GuessedClass=predicted label, HasChain=chain detection flag, IsPFAS=final judgment.
flagTbl = table( ...
    validNames, validCls, classGuess, hasChain', hasCF3', hasSulfonyl', isPFAS', ...
    VariableNames=["Name","TrueClass","GuessedClass","HasChain","HasCF3","HasSulfonyl","IsPFAS"]);
disp(flagTbl); %[output:95097666]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Calculate Persistence Proxies from Descriptors
%[text] With PFAS hits identified, we now quantify environmental persistence using three physicochemical proxies -- indirect indicators for environmental half-life, which is expensive to measure directly.
%[text] ### Concept: Three Proxies for Environmental Persistence
%[text] Direct measurement of environmental half-life requires expensive laboratory assays, so regulators use physicochemical proxies as early warning indicators (Wang et al. 2017, Cousins et al. 2020).
%[text] **Proxy 1: Hydrophobicity (LogP)**
%[text] LogP (logarithm of the water/octanol partition coefficient) is an indicator of how easily a molecule dissolves in oils and fats compared to water.
%[text] High LogP indicates strong affinity for lipids, leading to bioaccumulation in fatty tissues.
%[text] In PFAS, the ionic head group complicates LogP interpretation, so RDKit's Wildman-Crippen LogP is used as a structural proxy rather than a true partition coefficient.
%[text] Scoring formula: $score(logP) = \\text{clamp}(LogP \\div 10,\\ 0,\\ 1)$ (Score 1.0 at LogP = 10, negative values score 0)
%[text] **Proxy 2: Number of Fluorines (F Density)**
%[text] More C-F bonds increase chemical stability and slow degradation in the environment.
%[text] C-F bond dissociation energy (about 544 kJ/mol) greatly exceeds C-Cl (about 397 kJ/mol) and C-C (about 346 kJ/mol).
%[text] Scoring formula: $score(F) = \\text{clamp}(nF \\div 17,\\ 0,\\ 1)$ (Normalized to 0-1 based on maximum fluorine count of 17 in the set)
%[text] **Proxy 3: Water Solubility Proxy (TPSA)**
%[text] TPSA (Topological Polar Surface Area) is an indicator of molecular polarity expressed as an area.
%[text] Highly hydrophilic PFAS (high TPSA) dissolve easily in water, while highly hydrophobic ones (low TPSA) adsorb to sediments and accumulate in organisms.
%[text] Due to high concern at extreme values, scoring is done with a bell-shaped Gaussian function: $score(TPSA) = \\exp\\left(-\\frac{(TPSA - 40)^2}{2 \\times 30^2}\\right)$
%[text] Maximum score near TPSA = 40 A$^2$ (typical for long-chain neutral PFAS), with scores decreasing as deviation increases ($\\sigma$ = 30, heuristic for explanation).
logSection("A09", "Section 3: Calculate Persistence Proxies from Descriptors", "Analytics L3"); %[output:41dfe776]
DESCS = ["LogP", "TPSA", "HeavyAtomCount"];
descTbl = emk.descriptor.batchCalculate(validMols, DESCS);

logp_vec    = descTbl.LogP;            % N x 1
tpsa_vec    = descTbl.TPSA;            % N x 1
hatom_vec   = descTbl.HeavyAtomCount;  % N x 1

%[text] Count fluorine atoms from SMILES (fast: no Python call needed).
nF_vec = zeros(nValid, 1);
for k = 1:nValid
    nF_vec(k) = count(validSmiles(k), "F");
end

%[text] Calculate the three persistence proxy scores, each ranging from 0 to 1.
score_logP = min(max(logp_vec / 10, 0), 1);
score_F    = min(max(nF_vec / 17,   0), 1);
score_TPSA = exp(-((tpsa_vec - 40).^2) / (2 * 30^2));

scoresMat = [score_logP, score_F, score_TPSA];  % N x 3

logInfo("Persistence Proxy Statistics (PFAS Hits Only):"); %[output:8d1d49c0]
pfasIdx = find(isPFAS);
if ~isempty(pfasIdx) %[output:group:7e9cff83]
    logInfo("  LogP Score    : Mean = %.3f  Max = %.3f", ... %[output:2c6cd958]
        mean(score_logP(pfasIdx)), max(score_logP(pfasIdx))); %[output:2c6cd958]
    logInfo("  F Count Score: Mean = %.3f  Max = %.3f", ... %[output:4573deb4]
        mean(score_F(pfasIdx)),    max(score_F(pfasIdx))); %[output:4573deb4]
    logInfo("  TPSA Score  : Mean = %.3f  Max = %.3f", ... %[output:0b123b32]
        mean(score_TPSA(pfasIdx)), max(score_TPSA(pfasIdx))); %[output:0b123b32]
end %[output:group:7e9cff83]

%[text] Visualize the three proxy scores for all chemicals in a bar graph. PFAS hits should show high LogP and F count scores.
figure("Name","A09 Sec3: Persistence Proxy Scores"); %[output:89e64186]
X = 1:nValid;
bar(X, scoresMat, "grouped"); %[output:89e64186]
xticks(X); %[output:89e64186]
xticklabels(validNames); %[output:89e64186]
xtickangle(45); %[output:89e64186]
ylabel("Score (0-1)"); %[output:89e64186]
title("Three Persistence Proxy Scores per Chemical"); %[output:89e64186]
legend(["LogP Proxy", "F Count Proxy", "TPSA Proxy"], Location="northeast"); %[output:89e64186]
grid on; %[output:89e64186]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Weight Optimization Using fmincon
%[text] With persistence proxy scores computed, we now use `fmincon` (constrained nonlinear optimization) to find the optimal weights for combining the three proxies.
%[text] ### Concept: Constrained Weight Optimization for Multi-Criteria Scoring
%[text] The final "concern score" for each chemical is defined as the weighted sum of the three persistence proxies.
%[text] $score(k) = w(1) \\times scoreLogP(k) + w(2) \\times scoreF(k) + w(3) \\times scoreTSPA(k)$
%[text] The weights $w(1), w(2), w(3)$ represent the relative importance of each proxy and are constrained to sum to 1.
%[text] Experts may assign $w(2) \> w(1)$ as "C-F bond density is a more direct measure of persistence than LogP" (Buck et al. 2011).
%[text] To find the "optimal weights," we define a reference scoring rubric (correct targets).
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Compound Group | Target Score | Rationale |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | Long-chain PFAS (PFOA, PFOS, PFNA, PFDA) | 0\.80 | High concern (OECD Annex B substances) |
%[text] | Mid-chain PFAS (PFHxA, PFHxS, 8:2FTS) | 0\.60 | Medium to high concern |
%[text] | Short-chain PFAS (PFBA, PFBS, 6:2FTS, 4:2FTS) | 0\.40 | Medium concern |
%[text] | Non-PFAS Control | 0\.10 | Low concern |
%[text:table]
%[text] We minimize the sum of squared deviations from these targets subject to two constraints:
%[text] $w(1) + w(2) + w(3) = 1$ (weights must sum to 1)
%[text] $0.05 \\leq w(i) \\leq 0.80$ (each proxy must account for at least 5% and at most 80%)
%[text] The objective function is $f(w) = \\sum\_{k} (score(k) - target(k))^2$, which is a least squares fit.
%[text] Set the reference target scores for each chemical.
targetScores = zeros(nValid, 1);
for k = 1:nValid
    cls = validCls(k);
    nm  = validNames(k);
    if cls == "NonPFAS"
        targetScores(k) = 0.10;
    elseif any(nm == ["PFOA","PFOS","PFNA","PFDA"])
        targetScores(k) = 0.80;   % Long-chain, high concern
    elseif any(nm == ["PFHxA","PFHxS","8:2FTS"])
        targetScores(k) = 0.60;   % Mid-chain, medium to high concern
    elseif any(nm == ["PFBA","PFBS","6:2FTS","4:2FTS"])
        targetScores(k) = 0.40;   % Short-chain, medium concern
    else
        targetScores(k) = 0.50;   % Default for unassigned PFAS
    end
end

%[text] Define the objective function $f(w) = \\sum\_{k} (S \\cdot w - target(k))^2$ ($S$ is the proxy score matrix).
logSection("A09", "Section 4: Weight Optimization Using fmincon", "Analytics L3"); %[output:108a03fa]
objFun = @(w) sum((scoresMat * w - targetScores).^2);

%[text] Set the equality constraint (sum of weights = 1) and box constraints (lower and upper bounds).
Aeq  = [1, 1, 1];
beq  = 1;
lb   = [0.05; 0.05; 0.05];   % Lower bounds
ub   = [0.80; 0.80; 0.80];   % Upper bounds
w0   = [1/3; 1/3; 1/3];       % Initial estimate: equal weights

if hasOptTbx %[output:group:0f03409f]
    opts = optimoptions("fmincon", Display="off", Algorithm="sqp");
    [w_opt, fval] = fmincon(objFun, w0, [], [], Aeq, beq, lb, ub, [], opts);
    logInfo("fmincon optimized weights:  w_logP=%.3f  w_F=%.3f  w_TPSA=%.3f  (RSS=%.4f)", ... %[output:440bd764]
        w_opt(1), w_opt(2), w_opt(3), fval); %[output:440bd764]
else
    w_opt = w0;   % equal-weight fallback
    logWarn("Using equal weights [1/3, 1/3, 1/3] (Optimization Toolbox not available).");
end %[output:group:0f03409f]

%[text] Calculate the final concern score for each chemical using the optimized weights.
concernScore = scoresMat * w_opt;

%[text] Rank the concern scores in descending order and display the top 10.
[sortedScores, sortIdx] = sort(concernScore, "descend");
logInfo("Ranked concern table (Top 10):"); %[output:142c90f8]
for k = 1:min(10, nValid) %[output:group:73ed8365]
    i = sortIdx(k);
    logInfo("  %2d. %-18s  [%s]  Score = %.3f", k, validNames(i), validCls(i), sortedScores(k)); %[output:210d5204]
end %[output:group:73ed8365]

%[text] Display the ranking of concern scores in a bar graph with colors (red = PFCA, orange = PFSA, blue = FTS, gray = NonPFAS).
figure("Name","A09 Sec4: Ranked Chemical Concern Scores"); %[output:35030b91]
barColors = zeros(nValid, 3);
for k = 1:nValid
    i = sortIdx(k);
    switch validCls(i)
        case "PFCA",    barColors(k,:) = [0.85, 0.20, 0.10];   % red
        case "PFSA",    barColors(k,:) = [0.95, 0.55, 0.10];   % orange
        case "FTS",     barColors(k,:) = [0.25, 0.55, 0.85];   % blue
        case "NonPFAS", barColors(k,:) = [0.70, 0.70, 0.70];   % grey
    end
end
barH = bar(sortedScores, "FaceColor","flat", "HandleVisibility","off"); %[output:35030b91]
barH.CData = barColors; %[output:35030b91]
xticks(1:nValid); %[output:35030b91]
xticklabels(validNames(sortIdx)); %[output:35030b91]
xtickangle(55); %[output:35030b91]
ylabel("Concern Score (0-1)"); %[output:35030b91]
title(sprintf("Environmental Concern Scores (w=[%.2f, %.2f, %.2f])", ... %[output:35030b91]
    w_opt(1), w_opt(2), w_opt(3))); %[output:35030b91]
% Manual legend patches
patch(NaN,NaN,[0.85 0.20 0.10], DisplayName="PFCA"); %[output:35030b91]
patch(NaN,NaN,[0.95 0.55 0.10], DisplayName="PFSA"); %[output:35030b91]
patch(NaN,NaN,[0.25 0.55 0.85], DisplayName="FTS"); %[output:35030b91]
patch(NaN,NaN,[0.70 0.70 0.70], DisplayName="NonPFAS"); %[output:35030b91]
legend(Location="northeast"); %[output:35030b91]
grid on; %[output:35030b91]
yline(0.5, "--k", "Concern Threshold", LabelHorizontalAlignment="left", HandleVisibility="off"); %[output:35030b91]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Structural Similarity Heatmap of PFAS Hits
%[text] With concern scores computed, we now visualize structural similarity among PFAS hits using a Tanimoto heatmap.
%[text] ### Concept: Tanimoto Similarity and Structural Clustering
%[text] The Tanimoto coefficient between two molecules is calculated from Morgan fingerprints (circular fingerprints).
%[text] $T(A, B) = \\frac{|A \\cap B|}{|A \\cup B|}$
%[text] where $|A \\cap B|$ denotes the number of bits on in both fingerprints and $|A \\cup B|$ the total bits on in either.
%[text] T = 1.0 means identical fingerprints (structurally indistinguishable), T = 0.0 means no shared bits (completely dissimilar).
%[text] In PFAS, long-chain homologs (e.g., PFOA and PFNA) differ only in the number of -CF2- repeat units.
%[text] Therefore, the fingerprints are highly similar (T $\\approx$ 0.7-0.9), sharing all substructures except for the additional -CF2-.
%[text] In contrast, PFCA and PFSA have different head groups (-COOH vs. -SO3H).
%[text] Therefore, the Tanimoto similarity is moderate (T $\\approx$ 0.3-0.6).
%[text] A hierarchical clustering dendrogram groups the most similar structures, allowing visual confirmation of PFCA/PFSA/FTS subfamilies.
%[text] Since Tanimoto distance is non-Euclidean, we use average linkage (UPGMA) instead of Ward linkage (Ward assumes Euclidean space: Willett 1998).
logSection("A09", "Section 5: Structural Similarity Heatmap of PFAS Hits", "Analytics L3"); %[output:1070cd56]
pfasHitIdx = find(isPFAS);
nHits      = numel(pfasHitIdx);

if nHits > 1 %[output:group:16440e7e]
    % Calculate Morgan fingerprints for PFAS hits
    fps = cell(1, nHits);
    for k = 1:nHits
        fps{k} = emk.fingerprint.morgan(validMols{pfasHitIdx(k)});
    end

    % Construct Tanimoto similarity matrix
    simMat = zeros(nHits, nHits);
    for i = 1:nHits
        for j = 1:nHits
            simMat(i,j) = emk.similarity.tanimoto(fps{i}, fps{j});
        end
    end

    hitNames = validNames(pfasHitIdx);

    % Visualize as a heatmap
    figure("Name","A09 Sec5: PFAS Tanimoto Similarity Heatmap"); %[output:87284a5c]
    imagesc(simMat); %[output:87284a5c]
    colormap(hot); %[output:87284a5c]
    colorbar(); %[output:87284a5c]
    clim([0 1]); %[output:87284a5c]
    xticks(1:nHits); xticklabels(hitNames); xtickangle(45); %[output:87284a5c]
    yticks(1:nHits); yticklabels(hitNames); %[output:87284a5c]
    title("Morgan Fingerprint Tanimoto Similarity (PFAS Hits)"); %[output:87284a5c]
    axis square; %[output:87284a5c]

    % Hierarchical clustering: use UPGMA (average linkage) (Willett 1998)
    if hasStatsTbx
        distVec  = squareform(1 - simMat);   % condensed distance vector
        Z        = linkage(distVec, "average");
        figure("Name","A09 Sec5: PFAS Average Linkage Dendrogram"); %[output:6037bc54]
        dendrogram(Z, "Labels", hitNames, Orientation="left"); %[output:6037bc54]
        title("Average Linkage Dendrogram -- PFAS Structural Families"); %[output:6037bc54]
        xlabel("Distance (1 - Tanimoto)"); %[output:6037bc54]
    else
        logWarn("Statistics and ML Toolbox not available -- skipping dendrogram.");
    end

    logInfo("Tanimoto Statistics for PFAS Hits:"); %[output:02c0304e]
    upperTri = simMat(triu(true(nHits), 1));
    logInfo("  Mean = %.3f   Min = %.3f   Max = %.3f", ... %[output:23138b16]
        mean(upperTri), min(upperTri), max(upperTri)); %[output:23138b16]
else
    logWarn("Fewer than 2 PFAS hits; skipping heatmap.");
end %[output:group:16440e7e]
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Summary Report and Screening Dashboard
%[text] With structural clustering complete, we now compile all analysis results into a single screening report.
%[text] ### Concept: Communicating Screening Results
%[text] A screening report should show not only what is of concern, but also why it ranks that way -- the scores and weight of each proxy make the result falsifiable.
%[text] summaryTbl is a decision support table summarizing rank, compound name, classification, descriptor values, and concern scores.
logSection("A09", "Section 6: Summary Report and Screening Dashboard", "Analytics L3"); %[output:773525c1]
%[text] Construct a summary table for all chemicals.
[~, rankOrder] = sort(concernScore, "descend");
rankVec        = zeros(nValid, 1);
rankVec(rankOrder) = (1:nValid)';

summaryTbl = table( ...
    rankVec, ...
    validNames, ...
    validCls, ...
    classGuess, ...
    round(logp_vec,2), ...
    nF_vec, ...
    round(tpsa_vec,1), ...
    round(concernScore,3), ...
    VariableNames=["Rank","Name","TrueClass","FlaggedClass", ...
                   "LogP","nF","TPSA_A2","ConcernScore"]);
summaryTbl = sortrows(summaryTbl, "Rank");

logInfo("=== PFAS Screening Report ==="); %[output:6cb7f90e]
disp(summaryTbl); %[output:5630df8a]

%[text] Display a scatter plot with LogP (hydrophobicity) and F number (fluorine density) on two axes, with concern scores shown in color (turbo colormap).
figure("Name","A09 Sec6: LogP vs F Number (Concern Score)"); %[output:27da9e54]
scatter(logp_vec, nF_vec, 80, concernScore, "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.8); %[output:27da9e54]
colormap(turbo); %[output:27da9e54]
cb = colorbar(); %[output:27da9e54]
cb.Label.String = "Concern Score"; %[output:27da9e54]
clim([0 1]); %[output:27da9e54]
for k = 1:nValid
    text(logp_vec(k) + 0.1, nF_vec(k), validNames(k), FontSize=7); %[output:27da9e54]
end
xlabel("LogP (Wildman-Crippen)"); %[output:27da9e54]
ylabel("Number of Fluorine Atoms"); %[output:27da9e54]
title("Chemical Space View: LogP vs F Number (Color = Concern Score)"); %[output:27da9e54]
grid on; %[output:27da9e54]

%[text] ## Summary
%[text] - By combining three types of SMARTS patterns (perfluoroalkyl chain, CF3 terminal, sulfonyl head group), PFAS can be structurally auto-detected
%[text] - By normalizing the three proxies of LogP, fluorine number, and TPSA to 0-1, environmental persistence can be quantitatively compared
%[text] - Using fmincon's constrained least squares fitting, weights that maximize conformity to the reference rubric can be automatically derived
%[text] - Tanimoto similarity heatmaps and dendrograms visually confirm subclass structural relationships of PFCA, PFSA, and FTS
%[text] - By combining ranked concern tables and scatter plots, a dashboard meeting regulatory screening requirements (ranking, rationale, falsifiability) can be constructed \
logInfo("A09: Complete."); %[output:76b24ed6]

